{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655935"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:08:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:08:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18696"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18696"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11428"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79472"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11428"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64794"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10535"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79472"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sensation of thirst is crucial for maintaining body fluid homeostasis. The thirst centre responds to changes in plasma osmolality and volume status.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location of the primary osmoreceptors that trigger thirst?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebral cortex","Hypothalamus","Medulla oblongata","Pituitary gland","Thalamus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E contains specialised osmoreceptors in the organum vasculosum of the lamina terminalis that detect changes in plasma osmolality. These neurons are located outside the blood-brain barrier, allowing them to directly monitor blood composition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedulla oblongata\u003C/strong\u003E - While involved in other autonomic functions, this region does not contain primary osmoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E - Though involved in fluid balance through antidiuretic hormone release, it does not contain osmoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThalamus\u003C/strong\u003E - This region processes and relays sensory information but is not involved in osmoreception\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - While it may process conscious awareness of thirst, it does not contain primary osmoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen plasma osmolality increases by approximately 2%, these hypothalamic osmoreceptors trigger both thirst sensation and antidiuretic hormone release to restore normal fluid balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The thirst centre in the anterior hypothalamus is activated by increased plasma osmolality.","Osmoreceptors in the organum vasculosum of the lamina terminalis detect changes in blood osmolality.","A 2% increase in plasma osmolality is sufficient to trigger thirst sensation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64794"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18696"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explana